A black box in the car?
U.S. road planners are looking for a source of money to repair the decaying highway system, and believe they have found the solution in a small black box that fits in the dashboard of every car.
The devices, which record every kilometer driven and report the information to the authorities, are at the heart of a controversial attempt by Washington and state planning agencies to overhaul the outdated system for financing U.S. roads.
The usually rather boring field of road planning has suddenly sparked an intense debate with colorful alliances.
Libertarians have teamed up with environmental groups and advocate that the government can use the small boxes to record the kilometres driven – and possibly also where they were driven – and then use the information to calculate tax returns.
The Tea Party is horrified.
The American Civil Rights Association (ACLU) is also deeply concerned and expresses a number of privacy concerns.
But while one cannot agree on a course of action in Congress, several states no longer wait.
They are currently looking at how they can switch to a system over the next ten years where drivers pay per mile driven.
Thousands of drivers have already tested the tachographs, some of which are equipped with GPS monitoring.
This is truly a must for our country.
“It’s nothing we’re only going to possibly use,” said Hasan Ikhrata, executive director of Southern California’s Assn. of Governments, which plans to keep a record of miles driven among all California motorists in the state starting in 2025.
The way we pay these taxes will change.
The technology for that is there.
The initiative comes at a time when the Highway Trust Fund, which is funded from taxes that Americans pay at the pump, is broke.
In America, however, not as much is being refuelled as before.
Cars use less gasoline.
The state mineral oil tax of 18.4 cents per gallon (less than 4 eurocents per litre) has not increased for 20 years.
Politicians do not dare to raise the tax even by one cent at high fuel prices.
“Gasoline tax is simply not sustainable,” said Lee Munnich, a traffic law expert at the University of Minnesota.
His state recently equipped 500 cars with tachographs to test a mile-based payment system.
"This is the most sensible alternative in the long term," he said.
Bureaucrats refer to it as a mile-based user fee.
It is not surprising that the idea resonates with urban liberals, because the steering could be used, for example, to influence driving behavior in such a way that congestion and climate-damaging exhaust gases are reduced.
California’s planners are relying on the system to develop strategies to achieve the state’s ambitious, legally-enforced climate change goals.
But Pennsylvania Republican Bill Shuster, chairman of the House Transportation Committee, has also stated that he sees it as the most viable long-term alternative.
The free marketers of the Reason Foundation are also impressed by the idea of having drivers pay after a distance has been covered.
"This is not a tax that disappears into a black hole," explains Adrian Moore, Vice President of Policy at Reason.
People pay directly for what they get.
The movement is also backed by two former U.S. transport ministers who, in a 2011 report, called on Congress to move toward mile-based billing.
Last year, the U.S. Senate approved a $90 million pilot project that would have included 10,000 cars.
But the majority in the House of Representatives prevented the move, responding to the concerns of members of parliament from rural areas who represent people who often have to travel many miles on their way to work or to the city on a daily basis.
Nevertheless, several states and major cities are moving in this direction on their own.
The most dedicated is Oregon, which is currently recruiting 5,000 drivers for the country’s largest experiment.
These drivers will soon pay the mileage fees to the state instead of the mineral oil tax.
Nevada has already completed a pilot project.
New York City is considering this as well.
Illinois is testing it to a limited extent with trucks.
And the I-95 coalition, which includes the transportation ministries of 17 states on the East Coast (including Maryland, Pennsylvania, Virginia, and Florida), is currently exploring how to introduce the change.
The concept is not a universal hit.
In Nevada, where 50 volunteers were recently equipped with the devices, motorists were skeptical of the idea that the government could track any of its movements.
“Concerns about Big Brother and things like that were a big problem,” said Alauddin Khan, head of strategy and results management at the Nevada Department of Transportation.
People didn't want it.
When the test began, the ACLU of Nevada warned on its website: “It would be relatively easy to turn the tachographs into full-blown surveillance devices.”
There is no need to build a gigantic, bulky technological infrastructure that would inevitably be used to collect data about individuals’ daily movements.
Nevada is one of a number of states that are now looking for affordable technology that allows the state to track the miles driven, but not exactly when and where.
So, according to Khan, the public would also be calmer.
The hunt for this technology has led some authorities to a small startup called True Mileage in California.
The company did not originally start to help states tax motorists.
Rather, their goal was to gain a foothold in an emerging car insurance market where drivers are expected to pay based on miles driven.
But the devices she tested are also interesting for the road planners, because they do not work with GPS and only provide limited information, which are regularly uploaded by modem.
“People are more willing to participate if their speed and locations are not recorded,” said Ryan Morrison, CEO of True Mileage.
Major mistakes have been made in some of these public pilot programmes.
There are much cheaper and less intrusive ways to do this.
In Oregon, planners are experimenting with giving motorists a range of choices.
You can choose a device with or without GPS.
Or they don’t choose a device at all and instead pay a flat fee based on the average miles driven by all residents of the state.
Other agencies hope to be able to sell the concept of a suspicious public by equipping the devices with more features than fewer.
In New York City, traffic officials want to develop a device for taxation that can also be used to pay parking fees, pay insurance only for kilometres driven and collect speed data from other vehicles in real time, thanks to which drivers can avoid congestion.
“Drivers would be motivated to participate by the added value of the benefits offered by the system,” according to a planning document from the city.
However, some traffic planners wonder if all the talk about paying per mile isn’t just a huge distraction.
At the Metropolitan Transportation Commission for the San Francisco Bay area, officials said Congress could solve the problem of the bankrupt Highway Trust Fund simply by raising the fuel tax.
An additional one-time fee or an annual tax could be imposed on drivers with hybrid vehicles or other vehicles that consume little fuel, so that they also pay a fair share.
"There is no reason for surgery if an aspirin is sufficient," said Randy Rentschler, the Commission's Head of Legislation and Public Affairs.
When we do that, hundreds of millions of motorists worry about their privacy and numerous other things.
