What happens to my email on the way?
Email is actually an electronic letter.
When designing the Internet service, was e-mail technically implemented in a similar way to conventional mail?
When designing the early Internet services, the focus was on making communication possible.
For this reason, the basic technical protocols have not been careful to provide a stable foundation for a hearing-proof correspondence.
Therefore, a conventional email is more like an open postcard than a sealed letter.
If user "Anna" sends an email to "Benni", are the computers of the two directly connected?
In the first step, Anna’s e-mail program or browser sends the e-mail to the mail server of her service provider.
For example, if she has a Gmail account, it would be Google.
This mail server sends the content to the provider that Benni uses.
On the way, the mail can run through several other servers on the Internet.
Bennie can then call the content at his provider.
Are traditional e-mails being read on their way through the net?
Most e-mails are read several times on the way by software robots.
The sender's provider usually checks whether the mail carries a malicious program as an attachment.
A virus check is also carried out on the receiver systems.
In addition, the providers check whether it is an annoying and unwanted spam mail that is immediately deleted or at least sorted into a spam folder.
Do the robots have another task?
For systems such as Gmail, the robot also determines the information Google needs to place context ads.
If Anna and Benni communicate via Gmail about their upcoming holiday trip, Google can display corresponding links to holiday offers.
Do unknown people read e-mails?
The probability that unauthorized persons read an email is extremely low.
In theory, however, this is possible.
In companies, administrators often have the opportunity to read e-mail.
Law enforcement agencies and intelligence agencies also have legal ways to intercept or take notice of e-mails.
In addition, there are possible illegal spying actions.
Is it possible to protect e-mails from being read?
With an encryption according to the OpenPGP standard, an e-mail can be effectively encrypted against reading.
With a high technical effort, it is also possible to disguise the metadata of an e-mail communication, so that it is not even easy to recognize who has communicated with whom.
