George Kerevan: European unbundling gives Scots the choice
A new day, a new horror story about independence.
This time we are warned that an independent Scotland is needed to join the Schengen area as a condition of EU membership.
This provides the keyword for stories about passport controls in Berwick and a barbed-wire border along the Hadrian's Wall.
Indeed, the Strathclyde template pointed to the potential economic benefits that more freedom of travel would bring to the rest of Europe, but it did not – as expected – play a role in the headlines.
Nor has anyone mentioned that EU member states often bend their strict rules when it is more favorable for them.
As Scotland is not currently part of the Schengen area, the continued non-compliance with Brussels would be only a small concession in return for what you really want from the Scots.
Actually, not a story.
And one that has already come in such a way in the years that it is already like a fossil: The first time I heard the "independence means passport control" duck at least 40 years ago.
An interesting point is lost in the constant repetition of this age-old story.
Why would you expect an independent Scotland to dance to the European whistle?
Why trade the London yoke for that of Brussels, especially now?
These are the real European news: the great plan for the unification of Europe, conceived after the war, has come to a standstill.
With the euro crisis, the project Europe has officially died.
Throughout the EU, parties that are hostile to the EU or want to throw the euro overboard as a common currency are gaining ground.
Even in Germany, the Eurosceptic Alternative for Germany party – founded only this year – was able to win just under five million votes in the Bundestag election in September, effectively driving the Free Democrats (the equivalent of the British Liberal Democrats) out of the Bundestag.
There has always been domestic opposition to the plan to create a federalist Europe.
The current economic crisis, however, turns out to be a turning point.
Because of the strict austerity policies imposed by Berlin and the European Central Bank in connection with the straitjacket into which the respective national economy is forced by sticking to the common currency, many people believe that the project Europe has gone too far.
The euro crisis has little to do with national governments causing excessive budget deficits – this was only the case in Greece.
Instead, the Eurosystem has pegged its members to exchange rates that are beneficial for German exporters – and German politicians would like to keep it that way.
Without the possibility of devaluation of the local currency, Southern Europe finds itself with a built-in productivity disadvantage compared to Germany.
The only option is to cut wages and public spending – spurred on by Berlin.
Behind the current budget and currency problems lies a deeper European productivity problem.
As a result of Brussels’ “green” energy directives – a code for subsidising French and German energy companies at the expense of consumers – European industry pays double for electricity and four times for gas compared to the United States.
This is a crippling cost disadvantage, as we have already seen in Grangemouth.
All the world’s wage restraints do not protect the European petrochemical industry from being cornered by cheap American shale gas.
As a result, a revolt is on the rise, especially in France, the former cheerleader of the EU.
After the war, France’s political elite saw the EU as a vehicle to keep Germany in check and to keep Paris on par with Washington.
But Berlin no longer needs Paris as a gateway to political legitimacy and has pushed Europe into its own economic policies, which the battered French economy is struggling with.
The result: Marine Le Pen’s right-wing, EU-hostile Front National has just won a decisive by-election, putting the ruling socialists in third place.
The Front National is now the most popular party in France with 24 percent of the vote – a timely warning for the British Labour Party that it cannot assume a right-wing split would automatically bring benefits to the left.
What does Le Pen do with her newly gained popularity among the white French working class?
It wants to use the EU elections next year to forge an anti-EU, anti-common currency bloc in the European Parliament.
If the anti-EU parties do well in these elections – and this is very possible – then for the first time such a bloc could dominate the European Parliament.
This is the point I want to make: in the not too distant future, the growing resentment against the EU and the common currency will come together to abolish the euro.
The EU will not disappear, but it will rather become something of the "Europe of (sovereign) nations" that General de Gaulle favoured.
Germany and a few of its satellite economies may stick to the euro, but France and southern Europe will return to their own currencies.
I expect the UK to distance itself from this project in the hope of ingratiating itself to the US.
However, Washington’s growing interest in the Pacific suggests that Britain will stand alone in the Atlantic rain.
Where is Scotland in all of this?
We can decide to be a region of (ultimately) Little England.
Or we can defend our own economic interests – including telling Berlin and Brussels what they can do.
I suspect Scotland could do quite well in a looser European alliance, provided we keep our own currency.
Cooperation with other, similarly thinking countries is easier in a non-federated Europe of nations.
Otherwise, we should consider doing the same to Norway and maintaining our economic independence.
The SNP government in Scotland is – remarkably – the most successful political movement against austerity in Europe and won a spectacular majority in 2011 due to the rejection of the proposed (and made) cuts that Labour Finance Minister Alistair Darling and the subsequent Tory-Lib Dem coalition were responsible for.
It would be ridiculous for Scotland to opt for independence now, only to be forced into austerity by Berlin and Brussels.
Early puberty: growing up faster
African-American and Hispanic girls tend to be more likely to reach puberty than their white peers, research shows.
Physical changes do not immediately mean puberty
There is no evidence that hormones or other chemicals are responsible.
Experts Believe Epidemic Obesity Is a Trigger of Early Puberty
The trend towards early puberty is less pronounced in boys
Former CNN correspondent Pat Etheridge is a journalist specializing in child health and family issues.
Should a mother be concerned if her daughter grows breasts and pubic hair at the age of seven or eight?
At the American Academy of Pediatrics’ annual conference this week in Orlando, Florida, pediatric endocrinologist Dr. Paul Kaplowitz stated that these early physical changes were relatively normal among American girls and were a new norm.
“I spend a lot of time trying to reassure parents – usually this is not a sign that puberty is happening quickly,” Kaplowitz explained.
Obvious signs of development, such as growing breasts, pubic and underarm hair, as well as body odor, appear in girls earlier.
Nevertheless, there has been only a slight shift in the age of menarche (occurrence of first menstrual period) in the last 40 years.
In the United States, the average age is 12.5 years, slightly less than 12.75 in 1970.
"When the development of breasts begins, it takes at least two to three years to menarche," said Kaplowitz, also author of the book "Early puberty in girls: The essential guide to dealing with this common problem."
Time is the most accurate test of how puberty progresses.
It is controversial what actually marks the onset of puberty, but it is "tired" when breast augmentation is accompanied by a growth spurt before the age of eight years.
In most cases, the process slows down or stagnates — something a pediatrician can closely monitor.
In the case of faster progress, tests by an endicronologist may be indicated, so that serious problems such as tumors or cysts can be excluded.
There are treatment methods for delaying early menstruation and warding off another consequence: premature aging of the bones, which can ultimately lead to inhibition of growth and thus small body growth in adults.
The recommendations for drug or hormonal therapy are based on the age of the child, the rate of development, the rate of growth and emotional maturity.
Psychosocial aspects are also important.
Kaplowitz is reserved about medication, but admits: “Suppressing puberty can mitigate behavior problems and the feelings of girls, being different from their peers.”
The other big problem is understandable: Parents just don’t want their very young daughters to have the period.
“They worry about the risk of pregnancy or how they handle the hygienic side,” Kaplowitz said.
“It was a shock,” recalls a woman whose daughter got her days when she was ten.
Even though there were initial signs and we had talked about menstruation, she was not emotionally prepared.
She came home scared and excited from school because she was the first in her circle of friends.
There are many widely published theories about the causes of early puberty.
But there is no conclusive evidence that hormones in milk or other foods, chemicals in the environment, or sexual messages in the media are causal.
Boys come into puberty in a similar way to girls before.
Kaplowitz believes that the most convincing premise is the epidemic of obesity.
He supported the conduct of a 2001 study on girls aged six to nine, which found a link between body fat and puberty.
Other research supports this conclusion, but there are many other factors that played a role.
In this country, African-American and Hispanic girls tend to reach puberty rather than their white peers.
There are different explanations for this.
Globally, early puberty seems to be influenced by all sorts of things, from economic conditions to climate to genes.
Another mystery: Although boys’ facial and pubic hair grows earlier, the trend toward full-blown earlier puberty is not as pronounced as in girls.
Other doctors at the AAP conference underlined the complexity of the issue.
The appearance of acne and pubic hair is common even in babies and young children.
"We need to be careful how we identify the true onset of puberty," said Dr. Lawrence Silverman, a pediatric endocrinologist at Goryeb Children's Hospital in Morristown, New Jersey.
Parents should not hesitate to get advice from their pediatrician on how to talk to their child.
"This may mean that you have to have a conversation earlier than expected," advised Kaplowitz.
If you stay calm, the child usually responds well.
Girls who bloom early need the assurance that the process is a normal part of life, even if it occurs earlier than thought.
Jumbo manufacturers argue over seat width in the face of large orders
There has been a dispute between leading aircraft manufacturers over the breadth of tourist class seats on long-haul flights, setting the tone for a bitter clash at this month’s Dubai Airshow.
The dispute revolves around the seat width offered to passengers on long-haul flights in the tourist class – not always the ones airlines strive for the most, but this designated space is the key to the efficiency claims on the latest Airbus SAS and Boeing Co. aircraft.
Airbus this week called for an industry standard requiring a seat width of at least 46 cm (18 inches) in the tourist class, but U.S. arch rival Boeing says airlines should decide.
The dispute comes at a time when aircraft manufacturers are vying to sell even larger versions of their twin-engine long-haul aircraft and expect record orders at the 17-21 November event.
How the rear part of the aircraft is designed – especially whether there are rows with nine or ten seats – is crucial to the stated economic results that the new “mini jumbo” design is intended to deliver.
Boeing claims its upgraded "777X" holds 406 people in tourist class seats that are over 17 inches wide, allowing ten per row.
Airbus says the competing version of the A350 will carry 350 people in 18-inch-wide seats in the tourist class, with nine per row.
Aircraft giants often distribute blows over technical details by means of advertising in the trade press.
Airbus is now appealing directly to the public in front of the Dubai Airshow, where the 777X is expected to make the race with over 100 orders.
Recently, the company unveiled an ad that could be the start of a new ad war, showing donors a picture of three people sitting squeezed together in a restaurant, along with the title, “Would you accept that?”
"Boeing proposes long-haul flights in seats that are narrower than regional turboprops," said John Leahy, Airbus' chief sales officer.
People are getting fatter in the face of changing dietary habits, but airplane seats have not changed radically.
Between the early 1970s, when the Boeing 747 defined modern long-haul travel, and the end of the century, the weight of the average male American between 40 and 49 years has increased by ten percent, according to data from the U.S. Department of Health.
The waist circumference of the average male American in the 21st century is 100.8 cm, according to U.S. health statistics.
Airbus says its rival is sticking to a seat concept from the 1950s, when the average body circumference of the newly christened "Jet Set" was narrower.
According to Airbus, studies have been carried out that show that an additional inch (2.54 cm) per seat increases the quality of sleep by 53 percent.
Boeing denies Airbus’ figures on seat dimensions, saying it is not at the manufacturers’ discretion to decide how airlines balance fares and set-up.
The company also explains that, according to research, the experience in the aircraft depends on more than the seat width.
“It really boils down to giving airlines flexibility so they can do what they think they need to do to be successful,” said Boeing cabin expert Kent Craver.
They don’t want us to dictate to them what makes them profitable.
You know your business better than anyone.
For passengers, it’s about more elbow room, but for manufacturers, it’s increasingly becoming an issue that can impact sales.
Behind the dispute is a race for aircraft orders with an estimated volume of at least $700 billion according to list prices in the coming decades, which could have a lasting impact on the export balance of the USA or Europe.
As Reuters first reported in July, the seat layout is the driving force behind the dispute over the new jets.
Both Airbus and Boeing claim 20 percent more efficiency per seat in their latest long-haul twin-engine designs than the market leader in this segment, the 365-seat Boeing 77-300ER.
Boeing’s statements on the results depend in part on the fact that the 777X, with its ten seats per row, is compared to the original design of nine seats in the 777.
The increased cost per unit is still lower than that of currently used machines with ten seats per row.
“Boeing is therefore squeezing more seats into its aircraft to make it more competitive with our products,” said Kevin Keniston, Head of Passenger Comfort at European Airbus.
On the other hand, analysts say full cabins with ten seats per row at existing 777s indicated that many passengers opted for the tighter arrangement, which could come with cheaper airfare.
“Eighteen inches of seat width would be great for passengers, but the reality is: from an economic point of view, the Airbus offering is controlled by the threat posed by the 777,” says Mary Kirby, cabin furnishing expert, founder and editor of Runway Girl Network.
Airbus and Boeing do not offer seats, but a catalogue of suppliers from which airlines can choose.
The world-traveling jet sellers even carry tape measure to measure the facility in the competition.
Even if they promote comfort, all manufacturers also offer jets with a highly compact design for low-cost airlines and regional flights.
Airbus offers an A350 with ten-seat rows, but according to its own statement has not yet sold one.
Until recently, Airbus has stressed the importance of greater cabin adaptability and offered wide seats at the aisles for some jets.
Without the support of the only other manufacturer of large modern jets, experts say the call for a new industry standard is likely to fizzle out but could distract from the wave of 777X sales.
New anti-nicotine vaccine could kill smoking pleasure
Scientists have developed an anti-nicotine vaccine that could spoil the fun of smoking.
A single dose of the vaccine could protect mice from nicotine addiction for a lifetime.
More tests are needed before testing on humans, which may take a few years, but Professor Ronald Crystal of Weill Cornell Medical College in New York said the initial results are good.
“We are very hopeful that this type of vaccination strategy can once again help millions of smokers who have tried to quit using all the methods available on the market, but have experienced that their nicotine addiction is stronger than these approaches,” said Cornell.
The new vaccine contains a harmless virus that has been modified to contain the genetic information needed to produce nicotine antibodies.
The virus selectively infects the liver cells, which then produce a constant stream of antibodies.
The antibodies chase down the nicotine molecules in the blood and neutralize them before they reach the brain, preventing a smoker from experiencing a nicotine high.
In trials, vaccinated mice given nicotine maintained their normal activity levels.
Mice without vaccination, on the other hand, had taken a "timeout," the researchers explained, a sign that the nicotine had reached their brains.
The experiments are described in the journal Science Translational Medicine.
Previous tobacco vaccines failed because they contained antibodies.
Vaccinations had to be given so frequently to maintain antibody levels that they were expensive and impractical.
But the cost of the new vaccine is likely to be significantly lower, as it turns liver cells into antibody factories.
As Professor Crystal said, a future vaccine for humans, if it was completely safe, could be given to children before they were tempted to try a cigarette, thus preventing nicotine addiction.
More likely, however, smokers would use it to quit.
"You know then that when they start smoking again, they don't feel any pleasure in it because of the nicotine vaccine, and that helps them to get rid of the habit," he explains.
British scientists said the findings were interesting, but at the same time warned that further research was needed.
