Regulations on electronic devices in aircraft remain in force in Australia for the time being
Australian air passengers will continue to have to switch off tablets and smartphones at take-off and landing, despite efforts in the US to loosen regulations for such devices.
The U.S. Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) allows U.S. airlines to change their regulations so that passengers can read, watch or play e-books on their devices during critical flight phases, provided they are in “flight mode.”
During most of the flight, passengers are already allowed to do so, but many people find it annoying that they are not allowed to read their e-books when taking off and landing.
Australian companies are watching the decision, which requires U.S. airlines to do a ton of work, but are not pursuing any immediate plans to change their regulations.
CASA also said it would look at the announcement, but stressed that restrictions on the use of electronic devices in critical flight phases in Australia remain in place.
"CASA currently has no specific regulations regarding the use of electronic equipment in aircraft," it said.
The issue is subject to regulations requiring airlines to maintain safety at all times and passengers to follow the safety instructions given by cabin crew.
Virgin has already had discussions with CASA about extending the use of its Wi-Fi entertainment system on flights, saying that it is open to change, but that it needs to be initiated by lawmakers.
“We would welcome a review of the approval of electronic devices by CASA, because we are convinced that this would improve the customer experience after we now offer (wireless entertainment) during the flight,” a spokesperson said.
Qantas said it will remain in the current rules until further notice.
“Our current guidelines state that electronic devices are not allowed to be used at take-off and landing, and we have no plans to change that at this time,” the company said in a statement.
The FAA regulations apply to U.S. airlines.
However, we are always interested in developments in regulations from which passengers can benefit, and will certainly take a close look at the FAA decision and the reasons behind it.
The decision has a different effect on US companies depending on the age of the fleet.
They must demonstrate that their aircraft can tolerate radio interference from mobile devices, and change manuals, training materials, hand luggage programs, and customer training.
“Once an airline has confirmed the tolerance of its fleet, it can allow passengers to use portable, lightweight electronic devices such as tablets, e-book readers, and smartphones at any height,” the FAA said in a statement.
In rare cases of poor visibility, the crew will instruct passengers to turn off equipment during landing.
The group also recommended stowing heavier equipment safely under the seat or in the compartments above the seats during take-off and landing.
Before the Revierderby against Schalke, BVB trailers with flare rockets had taken care of ugly scenes in the Veltins Arena.
Borussia Dortmund then announced harsh consequences.
