Pawnshops are booming in Singapore as the crisis has arrived in the middle class
In a pawn shop in Singapore’s Bendemeer shopping mall, Janani Amirthalinga exchanges a gold bangle, a ring and a pair of earrings to pay her daughters’ school fees.
“My husband and I have just bought a house, all my money is in it,” Amirthalinga says.
Although she earns 3,000 Singapore dollars (about 1,730 euros) each month as an administrative employee and her husband also works, the monthly family income is not enough, she explains.
In fact, demand in parts of Southeast Asia – where household debt is increasing – is so high that ValueMax, where it made its exchange, became the third pawn shop listed on the Singapore Stock Exchange this week.
Bonding jewelry is not only a quick way to get money – $1,300 in the case of Janani Amirthalinga – but also almost as cheap as an unsecured bank loan.
Typically, pawnshops in Singapore charge an APR of 17 percent, which is just over the 15.4 percent that United Overseas Bank requires, a local lender with a branch in the same mall.
However, pawnshops offer the advantage that no verification of creditworthiness or proof of income is required here, which is why loans are possible faster than with banks.
For this reason, millions of people in the region turn to pawnshops after families feel the pressure from rising living costs as well as rising household and consumer debt.
After five years of robust growth since the global financial crisis and cheap loans due to a loose fiscal policy in the developed economic areas, lower- and middle-income families seek pawnshops to make up for the difference in a stuttering economy.
This week, the rating agency Standard & Poor described its growing household debt, mainly due to rising mortgages, as a risk factor for the creditworthiness of Asian banks.
According to the agency, Malaysia, Thailand and Singapore have the highest household debt in Asia relative to the gross domestic product.
Malaysia is at the top of the list with 80 percent of GDP, an increase of 60 percent in 2008.
Economists are also worried about the high consumer debt in Thailand, which has barely emerged from a technical recession this week.
On Thursday, the data showed a continuing weakness in exports and a decline in consumer demand.
“Ultimately, this means that with rising costs, people in the middle to lower segment (the income scale) will try to supplement their income wherever possible,” says Song Seng Wun, an economist at CIMB, a Malaysian bank.
Historic highs in gold prices over the past two years have further fueled the trend of pledging personal items as people seize the opportunity to turn family jewelry into cash.
In Singapore, about 70 percent of the pledged items in the city state’s 200 pawnshops are gold.
People say to themselves, "The price of gold looks good, let's pawn Grandma's gold chain and get it back next month."
The largest Thai pawn shop operator, EasyMoney, has seen a 20 percent increase in customers in its stores in recent months.
Growth in the pawn shop is so strong that ValueMax, operator of the branch in Bendemeer and 15 others in Singapore, wants to expand not only into neighboring Malaysia – where the company operates four houses – but also outside Asia, according to ValueMax CEO Yeah Lee Ching.
The company is funding this with 60 percent of the $66 million it raised this week with the Singapore IPO.
While some lenders have been caught in the crossfire because of high interest rates, Yeah explains that pawnshops not only offer cheaper interest rates than other lenders, but also do not directly increase debt.
"Customers are borrowing items they already own, and the liquefaction of personal valuables does not increase household debt," she explains.
The pawn lending business is increasingly socially accepted as short-term, secured financing.
Also, not all people who use pawnbrokers are in financial trouble.
Wealthy people from Singapore also come to ValueMax’s stores to pawn gold bars and Rolex watches, for which they receive up to 60 percent of the purchase price in cash.
Customers from every social class come to us.
“These include wealthy people who borrow short-term for a business or an investment, or small businesses who need to bridge cash flow bottlenecks,” says Yeah.
Sometimes they just need money very quickly.
