“The government has put together an emergency rescue package that we believe addresses the unique challenges facing the state,” Plibersek said.
The $325 million package includes $31 million in emergency election assistance.
Another 2,600 surgeries, including orthopedic procedures and treatments for cataracts, are to be carried out to eliminate residues.
In addition, there is money for day clinics in Hobart and Launceston, better aftercare after inpatient stays, specialist training, mental health services and the introduction of a system for electronic recording of health data in local hospitals.
“These investments are in line with the ideas that clinic staff told me were the best way to improve the Tasmanian health care system,” said Tanya Plibersek.
The Minister insisted on the Tasmanian Government’s strict reporting and accountability.
The state must maintain the current level of funding to receive money from the Commonwealth and report monthly on where the additional funds were spent.
A three-member commission will be established to ensure that the state provides health services as effectively and efficiently as possible.
As Wilkie explained today, the $325 million would be of little use if “they are not accompanied by genuine reforms that put the public Tasmanian health system on a more sustainable course.”
Nevertheless, he praised the government for responding to his request for urgent assistance, which he first expressed to the Prime Minister in early May.
"I am confident that federal aid will make a major contribution to removing the state's public health system from the worry list," Wilkie said.
According to the state government, these electoral benefits will largely offset recent cuts.
But the health policy spokesman for the opposition at the federal level, Peter Dutton, is of the opinion that today's announcement is only a "pavement solution".
“We are in the situation today because the Labor state government has withdrawn $430 million from the health care system,” he told ABC TV.
It cannot be that a state government rips almost half a billion dollars out of the system and puts 300 million in the Commonwealth and then pretends to be good news.
Dutton called on Plibersek to guarantee that not a single dollar of the bailout would be spent on additional bureaucracy.
