Syria has destroyed its ability to produce chemical weapons, a monitoring group says
Syria has destroyed key facilities for the production of chemical weapons and poison gas munitions, the global chemical weapons monitoring group said on Thursday, as heavy clashes occurred in the north of the country near one of the sites where suspected toxic substances are stored.
Also on Thursday, a Syrian activist group announced that more than 120,000 people had been killed since the beginning of the civil war almost three years ago.
The announcement by the Organization for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons (OPCW) came a day before the date on
November 1, which the Hague-based organization Damascus had set up to destroy or make “inoperable” all facilities for the production of chemical weapons, including all machinery for mixing chemicals into poison gas and filling ammunition.
The completion of this process, which is essentially the first stage of destruction, is an important milestone of an ambitious timetable aimed at the destruction of all chemical weapons in Syria by mid-2014.
The destruction of the facilities means that Syria can no longer produce new chemical weapons.
Damascus has yet to begin destroying its weapons and supplies.
It is estimated that there are about 1,000 tons of chemicals and weapons in the country, including mustard gas and the nerve gas sarin.
The announcement came at a time when fighting was taking place in the city of Safira on Thursday, where experts say there is a production facility for chemical weapons as well as deposits, the UK-based Syrian Observatory for Human Rights said.
The activist group, which tracks the death toll through a network of activists in Syria, said on Thursday that 120,296 people had died.
Of these, 61,067 were civilians, including 6,365 children.
On the government side, 29,954 of them belonged to President Bashar Assad’s army, 18,678 were pro-government fighters and 187 Lebanese Hezbollah militias.
Also among the dead were 2,202 deserted army soldiers and 5,375 opposition fighters, many of them foreigners.
On 25 July, the UN estimated the number of deaths in this conflict since March 2011 at 100,000.
This number has not yet been updated.
The conflict has forced about two million people to flee the country.
Assad’s forces have been fighting in Safira for weeks against the rebels, many of whom have ties to al-Qaeda groups.
The observatory said there were losses on both sides on Thursday, but did not provide any details.
The fighting underscores the danger facing chemical weapons inspectors, as their mission to liberate Syria from its toxic arsenal is a race against time in the midst of a raging civil war.
According to the OPCW, which works closely with the United Nations, the team “is now convinced that it has seen and witnessed the destruction of all the important production and mixing/filling facilities mentioned by Syria.”
Therefore, "no further inspection activities are currently planned."
Earlier this week, inspectors said they had completed the first round of inspections and visited 21 of the 23 sites identified by Damascus.
Due to security concerns, it was not possible to visit two facilities, the inspectors said.
On Thursday, the OPWC said the two sites had been abandoned, according to Syria’s statement, “and the chemical weapons program objects there have been moved to other named facilities that have been inspected.”
It was not immediately clear whether the site in Safira was one of the two facilities the OPCW inspectors were unable to visit.
Syria has presented a plan for the complete destruction of its chemical weapons, which must be approved by the OPWC Executive Committee next month.
"I take the hat off to the bravery and courage that you have all shown in fulfilling the most challenging mission ever carried out by this organization," Ahmed Uzumcu, the director general of the monitoring organization, said in a comment published by OPCW.
For three years now, the mainly Sunni Muslim rebels have been fighting a split from Shiite Islam in this civil war against Assad’s government and its security forces, which include many members of the Alawites.
In view of further developments, the head of the observation group, Rami Abdurrahman, said there was a strong explosion at an air defense facility in the Syrian coastal province of Latakia on Wednesday.
The cause of the explosion is unknown, he said.
Wrath over judgment for Bali bombers
Survivors and relatives of the 202 people who died in the 2002 Bali bombing reacted with anger at the verdict for the last of the instigators to be brought to justice, as they believed Umar Patek should be shot to death.
Patek, who spent nearly ten years on the run as one of Southeast Asia’s most wanted people, was sentenced yesterday to 20 years in prison for his role in building explosive devices for the bombing.
With suspension, he could be released after 15 years.
The 45-year-old was found guilty of mass murder for attacking two nightclubs in Kuta’s popular tourist district, which killed 202 people, including 88 Australians, and injured many others.
He was also convicted of a number of terrorism-related charges, including a wave of explosive attacks on churches in Indonesia on Christmas Eve in 2000.
The prosecution had demanded a life sentence, even if they could have applied for the death penalty for the man who is also called "Demolition Man" because of his reputation as a master bomb maker.
The decision has brought painful memories to June Corteen, a mother from Perth who lost her 39-year-old twin daughters Jane and Jenny in the devastation wrought by Patek and his co-conspirators nearly a decade ago.
Fighting with tears, she said Patek should have been sentenced to death.
I really mean, he should follow in the footsteps of the other guys.
"You should put him in front of a firing squad," Corteen told AAP.
I have to live every day with the fact that I will not have any more grandchildren and I will never see my daughters again.
The Sari Club was razed to the ground on October 12, 2002, shortly after 11 p.m., when a massive bomb exploded in a small truck parked in front of the nightclub.
Peter Hughes was at Paddy's Bar, where just 20 seconds earlier a suicide bomber exploded a backpack filled with explosives.
He fell into a coma for a month after the attack and "died" three times while hanging on to a life support system.
Hughes said Patek deserved the same fate as the three other members of the terror cell Jemaah Islamiah – Amrozi, Mukhlas and Imam Samudra – who were responsible for the massacre and were executed four years ago.
Really, this guy should get the death penalty before anyone else.
To keep him alive – no, there is no reason to keep him alive.
Getting 20 years after killing 202 people and injuring many hundreds is not much.
Patek is the last of the Bali bombers to stand trial.
He evaded arrest for nearly a decade, but was eventually apprehended in January 2011 in the Pakistani city of Abbottabad, where U.S. forces killed former al-Qaeda chief Osama bin Laden just four months later.
During the trial, an FBI agent testified that intelligence reports had indicated that Patek was in Pakistan to meet with bin Laden with the aim of rebuilding the link between Southeast Asian terrorist groups and al-Qaeda.
"He didn't turn himself in," said Corteen.
Until recently, he has shown no remorse for how much suffering he has inflicted on other people.
The verdict came ahead of the ten-year anniversary of this year’s attack, which is celebrated with commemorations in Bali and Australia.
“There will be a lot of tears this year,” Corteen said.
Patek can still appeal his verdict.
FAA: Passengers can now use electronic devices on airplanes (but not make cell phone calls)
From departure to landing, passengers can now use their electronic devices to read, work, play, listen to music and watch movies, but can’t make phone calls, according to new guidelines issued Thursday by the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) in the United States.
However, passengers should not expect these changes to be implemented immediately.
How quickly they will be implemented depends on the airline, FAA employee Michael Huerta explained at a press conference.
Airlines must demonstrate to the FAA that aircraft comply with the new guidelines and that they have updated the flight crew’s training manuals as well as the regulations governing the stowage of the equipment in accordance with the new regulations.
The FAA said it had already received plans from some airlines to expand the use of portable electronic devices in aircraft.
Among these airlines were Delta and JetBlue.
"Depending on the state of the plan, we could very soon approve the expanded use of electronic devices," the FAA said in a statement.
Currently, passengers have to turn off smartphones, tablets and other devices when the aircraft doors are closed.
They may not take off until the aircraft has reached a height of three kilometres and the captain gives the green light.
When entering the landing approach, the passengers must switch them off again and may not take them off again before the plane has landed.
Under the new guidelines, airlines whose aircraft are protected against electronic interference could allow their passengers to use the devices during take-off, landing and on the runway, the FAA said.
Most new commercial aircraft and other aircraft that have been converted to use Wi-Fi at higher altitudes should meet the criteria.
Laura Glading, president of the Professional Association of Professional Flight Attendants, welcomed the changes.
“If the new regulation is implemented safely – and we are working closely with the airline in this regard – both sides will benefit,” Glading said.
To be honest, we are tired of having to feel like watchers on this topic.
Nevertheless, internet connections for surfing, exchanging e-mails, text messages or downloading data under three kilometers remained prohibited, the authority explained.
Passengers are asked to put smartphones, tablets and other devices into flight mode.
So still no "Words With Friends", the Scrabble-like online game that actor Alec Baldwin played on his smartphone in 2011, when he had to leave a jet of American Airlines in public effect because he refused to turn off the device while the plane was parked at the gate.
And heavier devices such as laptops must still be stowed away, as there is a risk of injury if they fly through the cabin.
Mobile phone calls during the flight will also remain prohibited.
The regulatory authority for telephone calls lies with the Federal Communications Commission (FCC), not the FAA.
FAA may lift ban on certain electronic devices at take-off and landing
Last month, Mark Rosenker of the National Transportation Safety Board, a national transportation safety expert on CBS News, said cell phones were still considered a risk.
"Mobile phones are really a problem, not just because they could potentially cause interference to navigation devices, but because we know from the FCC that transmission from the air can also interfere with transmitter masts," said Rosenker.
An industry advisory committee set up by the FAA to investigate this issue last month recommended that the government allow wider use of personal electronic devices.
In recent years, pressure on the FAA has increased to loosen restrictions on use.
Critics such as Democratic Senator Claire McCaskill from Missouri argue that there are no valid security reasons for the ban.
The restrictions are also increasingly difficult to enforce because the use of the devices has become ubiquitous.
Some studies say that up to a third of passengers forget or ignore switching off the device.
The FAA began restricting the use of electronic devices by air travelers in 1966 after reports of disruptions to navigation and communication devices by passenger-carried FM radios became known, which were the latest technology trend at the time.
New aircraft are far more dependent on electrical systems than previous generations of aircraft, but they are also designed and approved by the FAA so that they don’t mind electronic interference.
Airlines have been offering passengers Wi-Fi for several years now when the altitude is reached.
The planes adapted to Wi-Fi systems are also less sensitive to interference.
The vast majority of passenger aircraft should be fit for increased use of electronic devices under the new guidelines, Huerta said.
Today’s electronic devices generally emit much less radio radiation than previous generations.
E-readers, for example, emit only minimal radiation when you turn the page.
However, when downloading or sending data, the transmission values are stronger.
Among the advocates for easing restrictions on device use by passengers is Amazon.com.
In 2011, company employees loaded a passenger plane full of Kindle e-readers and made a test flight to identify problems, but could not detect any.
Members of the FAA Advisory Committee expressed mixed feelings about the risk involved in using equipment.
Douglas Kidd of the National Association of Airline Passengers said he believed the disruption caused by the devices was real, even if the risk was minimal.
Other committee members said there were only isolated reports of pilots talking about aircraft systems being disrupted by the devices, and most of them are very old.
However, the committee recommended that the FAA allow pilots to order passengers to switch off equipment when instrument landing in low visibility conditions.
A group from the travel industry welcomed the changes and described them as a reasonable adjustment for travelers who today would be extensively equipped with technology.
“We are pleased that the FAA recognizes that a pleasant passenger experience is not inconsistent with safety,” said Roger Dow, CEO of the U.S. Travel Association.
