When she was released, the water rattle was fit and healthy again.
Is Europe’s elite ready to do business with Britain?
Business for Britain was launched in April with the intention of bringing the economy together and defining what those who provide prosperity and work in the UK want to change about our relations with the EU.
To this end, we commissioned the largest and most comprehensive survey of UK business leaders and asked them what they think about the UK, the economy and the EU.
YouGov surveyed more than 1,000 business leaders, representing roughly UK company sizes, sectors and regions.
The results of the survey will surprise many.
We have found that the vast majority of companies now export outside Europe, focusing on countries that are modernizing and growing, while countries in the EU are stagnating.
They want the government to favour new trade links with countries such as China, India and Brazil, rather than the long and exhausting process of reforming the obscure EU institutions.
When asked about their views on certain legally regulated issues – from antitrust law to product legislation – the majority of business leaders believe that control over these key competences should be taken back to Westminster.
There was general dissatisfaction with the single market because, according to the companies, the costs of the Brussels regulations would now outweigh the benefits of being part of Europe’s trade zone – even 40 percent of large companies agreed with the one that is traditionally the most Europe-friendly.
Finally, and this probably says it most, our survey of business leaders revealed that a clear majority of the UK wants a course towards changing the agreement and a relationship with the EU based on trade, not politics.
This insight, which can be found among companies of all sizes and leading corporations, shows that the economy is pushing for a "meaningful change" that will bring the heft of action back to the UK.
It’s about a lot – a change in the agreement and better conditions for Britain would lead to a 16% change of opinion in favour of remaining in the EU in a referendum.
The Prime Minister should have no doubt: this survey shows that the UK economy is behind his plan for renegotiating the UK’s terms for EU membership.
It also shows that the companies expect a renegotiation of a significant shift in the balance of power back to the UK.
A better deal for the UK economy is possible and increasingly necessary as the eurozone moves towards a closer economic and fiscal union.
The priority must be jobs and growth in the UK, as the result of our survey shows, which means an increased focus on trade for businesses and a fundamental change in the Brussels approach to regulation.
Gazprom’s Alexei Miller calls Bulgaria’s pipeline the beginning of a new gas era
The start of construction of the South Stream pipeline in Bulgaria marks the start of one of the largest European energy projects, the Gazprom board said.
“Today’s event is a milestone: Construction work on the Bulgarian section of the South Stream gas pipeline, the largest and most important project in Europe, has begun,” Gazprom CEO Alexei Miller said in a statement.
The project is a key element for the energy security of the entire European continent.
