Hearing before the Royal Commission: Two YMCA employees accused of sexual assault charges against Jonathan Lord
Two New South Wales (NSW) YMCA employees were charged with child sex offences before allegations were made against Caringbah nurse Jonathan Lord in 2011, according to the Royal Commission on Child Sexual Abuse.
However, in the opening statement before the Commission, the YMCA had stated that “in the organisation one had never had to deal with an incident of child sexual abuse”.
Chief Executive Phillip Hare was questioned about one case where one YMCA employee had been charged with child pornography offences and another in which a YMCA Caringbah Hall sports teacher had been convicted of abusing children entrusted to him in 1991.
Hare told Gail Furness, a lawyer assisting the commission, that he knew about the first case, but did not know about the second.
He acknowledged that the YMCA’s opening statement to the Commission was also inaccurate in claiming that “there have been external reviews of the YMCA that have recognized the YMCA as at the forefront of child safety.”
Rather, evidence before the Commission shows that the YMCA was informed that it received the second lowest rating of four possible in a quality audit conducted by the Department of Education and Communities (Ministry of Education) in August of that year.
Hare, who joined the YMCA at the age of 21, admitted that management had failed “from me on down” at Lord’s hiring and failed to ensure that employees were aware of their obligations to report violations of child safety guidelines.
Lord had been convicted earlier this year of sexually assaulting twelve boys during his two-year tenure with the YMCA.
He was sentenced to at least six years in prison.
Hare denied, however, that the YMCA had a cultural issue that prevented employees from reporting Lord’s child safety violations.
The staff said they had observed violations, including Lord being alone with children, caring for them privately as a babysitter, letting them sit on his lap, telling one that he loved it, and letting children play with his cell phone.
Danielle Ockwell, whose supervisor was Lord and who asked for child protection training because she was concerned about his behavior, testified that Child Services Manager Jacqui Barnat, who was Lords’ supervisor in the YMCA Caringbah, was “very intimidating and very unapproachable most of the time.”
The CEO stated that he would not accept statements from employees that they did not dare to report to their superiors.
Instead, he said, their friendship with Lord had impaired their judgment, so they did not report him.
Hare explained that he had informed the board of the YMCA NSW of his view that the lesson the organization had to learn from the “Jonathan Lord incident” was “not the reporting” by staff, and the board had agreed to it.
Hare said the decision to urge employees to sign confidentiality obligations shortly after the allegations arose had been made by YMCA’s Children’s Services Director Liam Whitley.
He said this was intended to prevent evidence from being contaminated, but it was “overzealous” and poorly implemented.
The YMCA NSW was not a safe organization for children during the period when Jonathan Lord was employed there between 2009 and 2011, Professor Stephen Smallbone of Griffith University, an expert on child sexual abuse, told the commission.
He explained that there had been “serious problems” in hiring, reviewing, training, and supervising employees.
The hearing was adjourned until 20 December.
