Scientists were able to shed more light on how a dog’s tail wagging relates to his mood.
Previous research had shown that happy dogs wobbled more to the right with the tail (from the dog's point of view), while in nervous dogs it was the left side.
But now scientists say that other dogs can perceive and respond to these subtle differences.
Professor Georgio Vallortigara, a neuroscientist at the University of Trento, said: "It is well known in humans that the left and right hemispheres of the brain respond differently to stimuli that evoke positive or negative emotions."
Here we have tried to look at this in other species.
He also noted that in dogs, just like in humans, the right hemisphere of the brain is responsible for the movement of the left side and vice versa, and that the two hemispheres play different roles in the feelings.
To learn more about how dogs respond to their conspecifics’ lateral tail wagging, the researchers monitored the animals while watching other dogs’ movies.
They measured the heart rate of the four-legged friends and analyzed the behavior.
We will probably soon understand why the tail moves in one direction or the other.
Professor Vallortigara said: “We showed the dogs movies with dogs – either a lifelike version or a silhouette to eliminate distracting other aspects, and we were able to control the movement of the tail more to the left or right.”
When the animals saw how an otherwise expressionless dog moved the tail to the right (as seen from the wagging dog’s perspective), they remained completely relaxed.
But if the tail tilt was mainly to the left (again from the dog wagging perspective), their heart rate rose and they looked restless.
According to Professor Vallortigara, the dogs do not intentionally communicate with each other through these movements.
Rather, he is convinced that the dogs would have learned from experience what movements they should be worried about and when they should not.
He said: "If you have different encounters with other dogs and the wagging of the tail in one direction is more associated with friendly behavior and the right side produces less friendly behavior, then you react based on these experiences."
The researchers say the findings could help dog owners, veterinarians, and trainers better understand their animal’s emotions.
John Bradshaw, an expert in dog behaviour and a visiting fellow at the University of Bristol’s Faculty of Veterinary Medicine, said this was not the first study to examine whether left and right are important for dogs.
Last year, a team from the University of Lincoln found that dogs turn their heads to the left when they look at an aggressive dog, and to the right when it’s a satisfied dog.
Another research paper at the University of Victoria in Canada said: “Dogs are more likely to approach a robot dog when its ‘tail’ wags left rather than right rather than getting restless – just the other way around than in the Italian study.”
According to him, the differences could be due to the fact that the dogs in the various studies did not interpret the animals in the films or the robot dogs as dogs.
A study of how dogs respond to real dogs could help, he explained.
“While there is considerable evidence for many different mammals that the two hemispheres of the brain are used for different purposes, many of the details have yet to be determined – and dogs are no exception,” Bradshaw said.
However, since their behavior can be easily recorded, it will probably not be long before we understand why the tail sometimes moves in one direction, sometimes in the other.
