Pope Francis appoints first cardinals in February
Pope Francis will for the first time appoint new cardinals to the Catholic Church on February 22, as the Vatican announced on Thursday.
Cardinals are the highest-ranking clerics in the Catholic Church after the Pope, and they are also the ones who elect a Pope, so Francis will appoint the first group of men who will ultimately participate in the election of his successor.
There are currently 201 cardinals.
However, a cardinal who has reached the age of 80 can no longer participate in the papal election – this falls to a group of 120 “voting cardinals”.
In a statement announcing the news, Father Federico Lombardi, a Vatican spokesman, said there would be a meeting of all cardinals before the ceremony to appoint the new cardinals, also known as the consistory, was held.
“Pope Francis has decided to announce his decision to convene the consistory in February in advance so that other meetings that require the participation of cardinals from all over the world can be scheduled,” Lombardi said.
Jack Valero of Catholic Voices said the number of cardinals eligible to vote will likely have decreased by February.
He explained that a pope usually appoints as many cardinals as necessary to restore the number of cardinals eligible to vote to 120, and as many cardinals over 80 as he likes.
The consistory next year is significant because it is the first since the election of Francis in March this year, Valero said.
There is currently a certain overhang on the part of Europe and especially Italy.
“It will be interesting to see if the new Pope will appoint cardinals from the rest of the world to restore balance,” he said.
Forty percent of Catholics live in South America, but they have only a tiny number of cardinals.
The cardinals will also be the first to be called since the formation of the Council of Cardinals, founded by Francis, a group of eight cardinals from around the world charged with finding ways to reform the Church.
In the past, the Pope decided everything on his own.
“Now Francis has chosen these eight cardinals to help him,” Valero said.
He said it was “possible” for Francis to ask the cardinals for advice.
But so far we have not been in this position – this is all completely new.
Valero said bishops would typically be called cardinals from large places, but Francis was “full of surprises – so we don’t know who he is appointing.”
