It is called "The Audacity to Win" and describes Barack Obama's memoirs of the 2008 presidential election.
When I finish my patient records in the evening and go to bed, the book takes me back to a time when politics inspired millions and took the breath away from talking.
The election turned into a landslide victory and news anchors paused to highlight the historical significance of this hour.
My classmates cried with joy, and my parents collected all the newspapers they could find.
A young team of visionaries was on their way to the White House and the nation was ready for change.
When Obama took office in 2008, he had approval ratings of 82%.
And then I close the book.
Switching back to the present is a bad awakening, like being ripped from a dream.
It’s hard to remember these optimistic times – they seem to be a vague memory, a sad reminder of missed opportunities.
In the years since I first cast my vote, something has actually changed.
But it’s just not something I could have imagined.
I recognize the great and multifaceted things Obama has accomplished, from the passage of the Affordable Care Act for health insurance to the military withdrawal from Iraq, the end of the forced concealment of homosexuality in the army, and the killing of Osama bin Laden.
I, too, believe that the partisan blockade tactic has tipped too many aspirations with which our nation should be moved forward: immigration reform, a public option for health insurance, and the closing of Guantanamo Bay, to name a few.
But after defending the Obama administration countless times against colleagues and acquaintances, I have come to the end of my attempts at explanation.
I have reached a point of political desperation.
Republican blockade policies cannot explain why they allow the wiretapping of foreign heads of state or the killing of innocent children by drones overseas.
It cannot explain why the National Security Agency collects data about the private lives of Americans and why whistleblowers are being punished for disclosing state misconduct.
It cannot explain why Anwar al-Awlaki, an American citizen, was murdered without trial, nor why the public funding and spending limits are circumvented during the presidential elections.
It does not justify the results of a report that said the White House’s efforts to shut down the media were “the most aggressive ... since the Nixon administration.”
And more recently, it cannot excuse the inability to design a simple website in the more than three years since the passage of the Affordable Care Act.
I don't know if that's what I should have expected.
Whether I should have understood at the age of 18 that the government’s work could contradict the political campaigns that preceded it.
Obviously, the House of Representatives is not a predictable course, as an opposition party and random events such as the Newtown massacre shape public discussion.
But when I look at the above examples, they seem to be largely elected by the government itself.
And that bothers me the most.
I voted for Obama again in 2012, not because I was excited about his candidacy.
Mitt Romney represented a confusing and untapped alternative, he seemed unable to determine his direction and positions.
I had the impression that a second term for Obama, free from the pressure of future elections, would fulfill the hope we had heard about for so long.
But with Obama’s approval ratings falling below 45% this week, the return to 2008 has become all the harder with this book.
It awakens in me the longing for the many promises that have dissolved into air.
This week, I read a section in the book that describes how Obama suffered a serious loss against Clinton in the Pennsylvania primary.
In a meeting with the electoral assistants after the decision, he told his employees that they had to get back on track and follow the purpose of their case.
"I want us to find our magic again," he said.
We need to remember who we are.
It's five years later, Mr. President, and I couldn't agree more with you.
The views expressed in this comment are solely those of Nathaniel Morris.
