RBS suspends two foreign exchange traders
The Royal Bank of Scotland has suspended two traders from its foreign exchange department, according to two people familiar with the situation; this is another indication that the global regulatory investigation into suspected currency market manipulations is picking up speed.
Some of the world’s largest banks, including UBS, Barclays, Deutsche Bank and RBS, confirmed that they are working with the authorities on the investigation into the world’s largest financial market, where $5.3 trillion changes hands every day.
The two traders would be the first RBS employees to be suspended in the expanding investigation that the scandal surrounding the Libor interbank business entails.
The bank, which did not comment on the suspensions, confirmed this month that it had received requests for information from authorities.
“Our investigation on this issue continues and we are fully cooperating with the FCA and other regulators,” the bank said two weeks ago.
Last month, people close to the situation said the RBS had forwarded the records of emails and instant messages sent by and to a previous trader to the UK regulator, the Financial Conduct Authority.
This trader, Richard Usher, had left the RBS in 2010 and is now said to have been on leave from his current position as European head of Forex spot trading at JPMorgan.
Rohan Ramchandani, head of European spot trading at Citi, was suspended this week and Matt Gardiner, former chief currency trader at Barclays and UBS, was suspended from Standard Chartered this week.
None of these traders were accused of any wrongdoing.
Usher’s instant message group included bankers at Barclays and Citigroup, people close to the situation said.
UBS announced this week that it had taken steps against some of its employees after the Swiss regulator Finma said it was investigating an alleged manipulation of the foreign exchange market at a number of Swiss banks.
At least six authorities worldwide – the European Commission, Finma, the Swiss competition authority Weko, the FCA, the US Department of Justice and the Hong Kong Monetary Authority – are currently dealing with allegations that bankers have agreed on transactions in the currency market.
HSBC, Citigroup, JPMorgan and Credit Suisse have also launched internal investigations or received requests for information from authorities, people familiar with the situation said.
Banks scour instant messages and emails from several years in search of cases of misconduct.
News of these investigations has thrown traders into turmoil in an area that has been one of the most profitable of investment bank trading units in recent years, but has been under pressure this year as low currency volatility limits opportunities for speculators.
Some bankers have tried to downplay the affair, saying it is nearly impossible to manipulate the vast and highly liquid foreign exchange market, but leading traders believe this is not necessarily true.
A leading trader noted that despite the enormous daily volume in foreign exchange trading, the fragmentation of liquidity between the various trading platforms and the increasing use of its own internal platforms by banks means that “you can influence the market even with very low ticket prices”.
The news came the same day Credit Suisse announced that it had terminated a trader at its London Exchange Traded Funds office this week after causing a loss of just under $6 million late last year.
The Bank promptly informed the competent authorities and cooperated with them.
“We are sure that the trader acted alone and that the matter is contained,” Credit Suisse said.
