Egypt sworn in as first freely elected president
Mohammed Morsi takes the oath of office, but his day of triumph should not mean the end of political disputes in Egypt.
The Islamist Mohammed Morsi promised a "new Egypt" when he was sworn in as the country's first freely elected president, succeeding Husni Mubarak, who had been ousted from office 16 months earlier.
With his inauguration in front of the Supreme Constitutional Court, Morsi also became the Arab world’s first freely elected Islamist president and Egypt’s fifth head of state since the overthrow of the monarchy some 60 years ago.
He took the oath before the 18 black-robed judges of the court, which has its seat on the Nile and is modelled on an ancient Egyptian temple.
"We are striving for a better future, a new Egypt and a second republic," Morsi said at the ceremony, which was broadcast live on state television.
“Today, the Egyptian people have laid the foundation for a new life – absolute freedom, true democracy and stability,” said 60-year-old Morsi, a U.S.-trained engineer and member of the Muslim Brotherhood, a fundamentalist group that had mostly been targeted by the respective government as a banned organization since its inception 84 years ago.
Hundreds of soldiers and police guarded the building when Morsi arrived in a small car convoy shortly after 11 a.m. local time.
Only a few hundred supporters had gathered in front of the court to cheer on the new president, and unlike the presidential pageantry from the Mubarak era, traffic was only briefly stopped so that the auto convoy could cross the usually busy street that connects the city center with the southern suburbs.
Derided as an uncharismatic “spare wheel” of the Brotherhood, his personal prestige has increased since his victory and a Friday speech in which he presented himself not only as a candidate of the Islamists, but all those who wanted to bring the aspirations of the 2011 uprising against the authoritarian Mubarak to the goal.
"Egypt today is a civil, national, constitutional and modern state," Morsi, dressed in a blue suit with a red tie, told the judges in the wood-paneled chamber where he took the oath of office.
Later, Morsi went to the University of Cairo, where he was to give his inaugural speech.
He was officially greeted by an army band that played the national anthem, which he listened to in accord.
The military leader Field Marshal Hussein Tantawi was present.
On his arrival, he was greeted by hundreds of people in the largest lecture hall of the university with speaking choirs of "The army and the people are one hand".
Built in 1908 as a bastion of secular education, Cairo University developed into a stronghold of Islamist student groups in the 1970s.
On Friday, Morsi took a symbolic oath in Tahir Square, the birthplace of the uprising that led to the end of Mubarak’s authoritarian rule last year, and vowed to reclaim presidential powers that the military council had taken from the ousted head of state.
But by taking the official oath before the court and not before parliament as usual, he bows to the will of the military, indicating that the power struggle will continue.
