Tourism: Descent to the Romans
At a length of about 120 meters, a sewer from Roman times is preserved below Cologne.
If you visit Cologne, you will not pass the cathedral.
The two towers rise 157 meters into the sky and make it the second highest church building in Europe.
But only a few visitors, who marvel at the two filigree church towers, suspect that there is also a lot to discover under the cathedral.
Rainer Schulze is an expert on the Cologne underworld.
Meeting point for its guided tours is the Service Center of Cologne Tourism directly at the cathedral.
The tour begins quite unspectacularly: "We start in the underground car park," says Schulze.
In the seventies, the city fathers wanted a car-friendly city, and therefore only what was not too big remained of the remains of the old city wall.
Most users of the parking garage therefore also rush past the Roman remains today and only park their car.
But if you take a closer look, you will discover an archaeological site separated by metal bars in Parkdeck D2.
You can see about five meters high ruins made of hand-plate-sized stones.
"They are remnants of the Roman city wall, which was built in the second half of the first century AD," Schulze says.
Before it goes back to daylight, Schulze lets the participants on the upper park level take a look into a dark, 15 meter deep shaft.
This is the fountain of the old cathedral, which unfortunately is hardly noticed either.
The next stop of the tour is the praetorium, where the participants descend back down into the depths.
Here we experience the seat of the once most powerful man north of the Alps, the praetor of the CCAA.
What CCAA means, a visitor wants to know.
"The abbreviation stands for "Colonia Claudia Ara Agrippinensium", which in good German means as much as "city of Roman law and city of the Agrippinenser, founded under Emperor Claudius at the place of the altar for the imperial cult".
And the praetorium is the former governor's palace, the power center of the Roman Empire on the Rhine.
From the anteroom of the exhibition, a tunnel leads to the Roman sewer, which is preserved here over a length of around 120 meters.
"You can walk along the so-called Cloaca Maxima, if you want," Schulze encourages the guests.
Schulze has a surprise.
After getting the key at the ticket office, he leads the group to a 16-meter-deep, walk-in shaft.
"We are now in the mikveh, a ritual Jewish bath," he explains.
The Jewish community built their bath deep in the ground to get to the groundwater, which was essential for the ritual washings.
To this day, different water levels can be read in the lower end of the mikveh, whose origins date back to the eighth century, due to changing levels of the Rhine.
The mikveh will become part of an archaeological zone in the Town Hall Square, for which construction work is expected to begin shortly.
However, a few more years will pass before completion.
